    <text id="R1469647T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Union General Phillip Sheridan writes to Secretary of War Edwin Stanton to report
                    the January, 1865, return from Staunton, VA, of two scouts. The scouts reported
                    that talk in Staunton centered on the possibility of a Confederate withdrawal
                    from Virginia.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Hon. E. M. STANTON,<lb/> Secretary of War:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1865-01-05">January 5, 1865</date><time>--2 p. m.</time>
                        <name type="place">WINCHESTER, VA.,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>Four thousand troops will be sent from Stephenson's Depot at 10 o'clock
                    to-morrow. It will require that time to get transportation there. I will take
                    the necessary precaution to prevent desertions, as far as possible. Two of my
                    best scouts have just returned from Staunton. They represent a gloomy state of
                    affairs, and that the common conversation is that Virginia will be given up.
                    This information I send for what it is worth. It does not tally with the
                    information received from deserters from Richmond yesterday.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>P. H. SHERIDAN,<lb/> Maj.-Gen.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
